ranking noblewomen in sixteenth-century England. She wielded considerable political power in her local community and at court, and her social status and her commitment to religious reform placed her at the centre of the political and religious developments that shaped the English Reformation. By focusing on her kinship and patronage network, this book offers an examination of the developmentof Protestantism in the governing classes during the period. It begins by looking at the process through which Willoughby and her associates embraced reform, arguing that the spread of Protestantism among the political elite was an intermittent and complex process shaped in part by myriad kinship and patronage relationships: Willoughby and her godly associates played a crucial role in encouraging religious change in Lincolnshire through their patronage ofreformers and their support of a variety of domestic, educational, and religious institutions. It also demonstrates the importance of gender in the process of spiritual transformation, and shows how the changing religious climateprovided new opportunities for women to exert greater influence in their society. MELISSA FRANKLIN HARKRIDER is Assistant Professor of History, Wheaton College.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChurch and social problemsxProtestant churches. 0aProtestant womenvBiographyzEnglandzLincolnshire. 0aProtestant womenzEnglandzLincolnshirevBiography. 0aProtestantismxHistoryy16th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aWomen social reformersvBiographyzEnglandzLincolnshire. 0aWomen social reformerszEnglandzLincolnshirevBiography. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aModern History. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  afeminism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Pac